Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port.

**1. Add the test package:**
```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

**2. Write tests against the MCP endpoints:**
```csharp
public class McpTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/list",
            @params = new { }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }
}
```

**3. For Streamable HTTP (SSE) responses**, read the stream:
```csharp
var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request,
    HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);
using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

while (await reader.ReadLineAsync() is { } line)
{
    if (line.StartsWith("data: "))
    {
        var json = JsonDocument.Parse(line[6..]);
        // assert on each SSE event
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `WebApplicationFactory` runs the full middleware pipeline (auth, routing, serialization) — no mocks needed
- Override services via `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in test doubles (e.g., a fake database)
- Make sure `Program` is accessible (add `public partial class Program { }` to your entry point if needed)
- If your MCP server requires session state across calls, reuse the same `HttpClient` instance
